<gtr:grantCategory>Research Grant</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/G001898/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>A large body of research has shown that employee health and well-being is determined by a multitude of work and organisational characteristics. However, findings have often been inconsistent, for two main reasons:&lt;/p>

&lt;ul>
 

 &lt;li>First, the majority of research has focused on individual-level variables (eg job demands, relationships at work, social support, coping resources) and has largely ignored the impact of higher-level organisational characteristics (eg policies and practices, leadership, organisational change). 
&lt;/li>
 &lt;li>Second, although the study of work-related health is concerned with the individual within the wider organisation, research methodology has typically used single-level approaches. Inconsistent findings can have important implications for the management of work-related health.&lt;/li>
&lt;/ul>

&lt;p>The aim of this project is to understand which and in what way elements of the wider organisational context influence employee work-related health, using an appropriate methodology. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>It takes a multilevel approach by looking at the impact of both individual and organisational level characteristics simultaneously. In order to establish causal links, it also assesses relationships at multiple points in time. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>The findings of the project will help to extend current theory on the determinants of work-related health. They will also help to develop the necessary knowledge and skills for managing work-related health in a successful and sustainable way.&lt;br />&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2011-09-30</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2009-04-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>264777</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs><gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:description>The workplace makes a difference</gtr:description><gtr:form>A talk or presentation</gtr:form><gtr:geographicReach>National</gtr:geographicReach><gtr:id>8D47C745-0AC7-4E73-8289-4DCAD9744348</gtr:id><gtr:impact>Invited guest lecture, University of Exeter Business School, c.35 UK and international undergratuate students in business and management

