he characteristics of the job, and are as important as good leadership. This research has important theoretical implications because it offers an understanding of how healthy workplaces can be developed. In addition, it has practical implications for developing healthy workplaces and interventions to promote health and well-being. We are further expanding this line of research with new collaborators.</gtr:description><gtr:exploitationPathways>This research has important practical implications for developing healthy workplaces and promote employee health, well-being and productivity. First, organisations can use the short and comprehensive measure to assess the healthiness of the workplace. Second, the results can be compared with an extensive set of benchmark data of UK private and public organisations. Third, we have identified a number of principles of healthy workplaces that accompany the manual of the measure. Fourth, this research provides a missing understanding of the characteristics of healthy workplaces that can support individual well-being and productivity. Fifth, this theoretical development is the missing link between good job design and good workplace design and can as such lead to further research and conceptual developments. Sixth, the findings can be used to develop practical and actionable organisational interventions.</gtr:exploitationPathways><gtr:id>CD4BF20F-B054-4149-BE56-C7ED9A6784A7</gtr:id><gtr:sectors><gtr:sector>Aerospace, Defence and Marine,Agriculture, Food and Drink,Chemicals,Communities and Social Services/Policy,Construction,Digital/Communication/Information Technologies (including Software),Education,Electronics,Energy,Environment,Financial Services, and Management Consultancy,Healthcare,Leisure Activities, including Sports, Recreation and Tourism,Government, Democracy and Justice,Manufacturing, including Industrial Biotechology,Culture, Heritage, Museums and Collections,Pharmaceuticals and Medic</gtr:sector></gtr:sectors></gtr:keyFi